  <section>
    <title>Challenged Communications</title>
    <para>
      When commercial communications are not available, the SEC will
      attempt to make notification on radiotelegraph and then
      radiotelephone immediately on notification of the incident,
      and then once per hour.
    </para>
    <para>
      <note>
	<title>Radiotelegraph is far more reliable</title>
	<para>
	  Experience has shown that communications across the state on
	  radiotelephone is often challenging.  Stations should equip
	  themselves for radiotelegraph communications whenever
	  possible.
	</para>
      </note>
    </para>
    <para>
      Radiotelegraph notification will occur on the hour and
      radiotelephone notification at 15 minutes after the hour,
      until such time as either the MIARPSC or QMN net has been
      fully activated, or until the SEC leaves for the SEOC. 
    </para>
    <para>
      Communications within the state is not always possible on the same
      frequency.  Generally, it is straightforward to identify conditions where
      the standard frequencies are inappropriate.
    </para>
    <para>
      <table frame="all">
	  <title>Emergency Frequencies</title>
	  <tgroup cols="3">
	    <colspec colnum="1" colname="c1" colwidth="3*" />
	    <colspec colnum="2" colname="c2" colwidth="1*" />
	    <colspec colnum="3" colname="c3" colwidth="1*" />
	    <thead>
	      <row>
		<entry>Conditions</entry>
		<entry>Radiotelegraph</entry>
		<entry>Radiotelephone</entry>
	      </row>
	    </thead>
	    <tbody>
	      <row>
		<entry>
		  Normal conditions
		</entry>
		<entry>3.563</entry>
		<entry>3.932</entry>
	      </row>
	      <row>
		<entry>
		  Summer, daytime, conditions of high flux (typically above
		  140). Lower frequencies are too noisy to support
		  communications.  Absorption on 80 meters may be high.
		</entry>
		<entry>7.068</entry>
		<entry>7.232</entry>
	      </row>
	      <row>
		<entry>
		  Winter, nighttime, low flux (typically below 90).  Short skip
		  (within state) is not possible on higher frequencies.
		</entry>
		<entry>1.812</entry>
		<entry>1.932</entry>
	      </row>
	    </tbody>
	  </tgroup>
	</table>
      </para>
      <para>
	When the situation warrants, the DEC may also notify programs
	via the CMEN linked repeater system and/or the IRA link.
	Repeated notification, when required, will take place on the
	CMEN system at the bottom of the hour and the IRA system a 45
	minutes after the hour.
      </para>

